text: It comes down to choices, plain and simple, even when we're young we know the difference between right and wrong, especially if your brain works correctly. I'm in my late thirties, I grew up on everything in terms of entertainment.Â  I also had a verbal education from my elders. If we choose not to follow the advice of people trying to keep us on a "righteous path" - there's nobody to blame but ourselves, it starts within.Â  Are you able to see in-between the lines of a story or narrative, the lessons that are there in the Art.Â  I grew up listening to Mobb Deep and Hardcore Music, Boyz n da Hood, Menace 2 Society and lots of violent movies, Mortal Kombat videogames, didn't mean I wanted to shoot somebody or rip into somebody's chest with my bare hands, pull their heart out and hold it in the air in victory.Â  I grew up with people where some dabbled in â€œStreetLifeâ€ some went to â€œWorkâ€ or â€œStudiedâ€, like I said before, it comes down to choices. If you're easily influenced by entertainment or even peer pressure from your friends, that's something you have to learn to deal with quickly.... Â especially if you're a young person today.

text: "Our art is a reflection of our reality", "We're just rapping about what we experience". I think those are lame cop outs. If you are experiencing gangs, drugs, violence and you want change, you don't glorify those things, you show the ill effects of them. Rap about people strung out on drugs, with no hope, brain dead, begging for change. Rap about people in jail, living on instincts, always looking over their shoulder so they don't get shanked or raped. Rap about how violence begets violence. Rap about ignorance and what a devastating effect it has on people and how it's passed on from generation to generation. Rap about sexually transmitted diseases and the suffering that people live through with those diseases. Rap about women having kids at a young age and having the father abandon the family, and not being able to live a decent life, working two jobs, while your kids are being raised by violent video games and movies and gangster rap and getting shot, or strung out on drugs and your kids then saying, "It has nothing to do with the violence I put into my brain 24hr a day, 7 days a week." If you really WANT change, you can rap about that. Or you can rap about how to live your life with WISDOM. That's how you create change. Find Jesus.

text: While Cube talks about peaceful protest and rapping about what he saw in the hood he glosses over the negative impact his music had on a lot of people. I was a teenager in LA when NWA was at its zenith. It was an incredibly violent time,much,much,worse than it is today. There were a lot of kids who listened to their music and wanted to live the life they sang about. For a time it was the cool,trendy thing to be a gangster and their music was a big part of that. I'm not blaming NWA for causing this but I do believe they threw gas on the fire with their music. There are many people dead or in prison because they wanted to be just like the characters(they were playing a role,Cube never shot any cops) that NWA sang about.

text: This movie is going to be great. F. Gary Gray...the director of this movie and cult classic, "FRIDAY", did a fantastic job of capturing the intensity of that era. I grew up in LAÂ during the 80's as a childÂ at the time period this movie is based on. Witnessed first hand the environment that was the product of those times. Aside from my personal connection to the film, I also had the privilege of being an extra for one of the major concert scenes. The set wasÂ historically accurate and recreated the experience aÂ fan of NWA would have had. The director, the cast, the production crew, and even craft services (got fed pretty good), were cool with all the extras involved. It was a very long day. 3pm-3am. Some extras left early, but I stayed the entire shoot. Ice Cube was dope for performing music in between filming. To see a post-production trailer for the movie has impressed me with the amount of detail F. Gary Gray put into this film. Can not wait to view the finished project in August. #StraightOuttaCompton #IWasThere #WorldsMostDangerousRapGroup

text: When you've got solid character actors like Paul Giamatti (who I assume is Jerry Heller) involved, this has a chance to be a really good movie. I'm excited. I just hope its good...I was 10 when Straight Outta Compton was released and I listened to Kool Moe Dee and Run DMC...NWA was to the rap game what Nirvana ended up being to rock a couple years later: A seismic shift. If you were putting out a certain kind of music, people weren't listening to you. We can debate if that's good or bad, but what NWA did...unlike 2 Live Crew or Public Enemy, was literally CHANGE the way people went about producing and creating music within a genre. We still see Cube and Dre, but I don't think people really understand how NWA changed rap on a MAINSTREAM level...without even getting on the radio. Imagine if Taylor Swift or Sam Smith or One Direction or Iggy Azalea had to get their music out to the masses without ANY mainstream play. No radio, no Spotify, no Pandora, no iTunes...nothing. Just essentially enough curiosity about an album to drive it to platinum status. THEY DIDN'T EVEN GO ON TOUR! And they made an album that completely changed the game...forever. Still amazes me to this day. That's true talent winning out. That's why I hope this movie gets it right.Â

text: To all those Millenials that want to call out this music as being fake (ridiculous and typical), basically, if you were born after 1990 you have no opinion on Gangsta. Sorry but thats just how it is. I grew up in a time when m'fers were blastin this out the car, thuggin it, daily fights, getting jumped, weapons, taggin, lookin down, "what bitch", mean mugs, stares, back of the bus/train, gangs, PARTIES PARTIES PARTIES andÂ  GANGS EVERYWHERE from FOLSOM SAC MARIN RICH to SF OAK SJ MOD FRESNO LA and SAN D, this music inspired and was the background soundtrack, for everything crazy raw that happened in the 80s and early 90s. All of it whether good or bad, made you mentally tough. Like Fight Club, most of my generation can deal with most problems. Little lesson for the day. I know, I know, now everything is nerdy, safe and hidden behind some cutesy lookin icon and you just wanna get durty, and you want to have some cool part of our legacy. But sorry that was OUR time, fueled by the 60s and 70s movements. Like the Roaring 20s, We LIVED. You can have your smartphone.

text: People can say what they want. N.W.A. paved the unknown road to hardcore rap. They got a letter from the F.B.I. stating that there song fuck the police had resulted in the killing of 76 police officers and were ordered to cease and desist. They said FUCK THE POLICE. If you really watch the story about these guys you will see that they were revolutionaries in what they did. They along with public enemy & 2 live crew tested the 1st amendment and won. They took their cases to the supreme court and won. It was a point in time that tested the constitution and the bill of rights. These guys stood up for what they believed in and stopped at nothing to achieve this goal. whether you like them or not they had a revolutionary period that helped mold the 1st amendment freedom of expression & speech. Instead of people knocking them they should be thanking them regardless if you like what they do or not. text: Movie looks pretty good, can't lie. Not sure if I'll be checkin it out when it hits theaters, but will definitely be checkin for it on dvd and online when it gets released. Biopics tend to over dramatize things sometimes, so the accuracy can be off. I doubt that Cube, although my favorite of all time, added the part of his life where he was gettin bused to Taft High School from South Central, which is like worlds away from where he lived. Truth was Cube's mom, Mrs. Jackson, was tired of Cube getting jumped and robbed because he didn't wanna join his neighborhood gang. Wonder if Dre's woman beating past will be added. I'm sure Eazy and Ren's past of runnin with the Kelly Park Crips in Compton will for sure be in there, because that's the type of stuff that sells movies. But according to the OG Tweety Bird Loc, Ren got ran off the set a long time ago, and Eazy stopped coming around his big homies when NWA blew up. Yella's story was never too compelling, just always known as the DJ who moved from LA to Riverside when the group started to go their separate ways.Â   I did notice that they got Suge giving somebody a beat down (the guys wearing all the red lol). That part was more than likely depicting Suge getting Dre out of his Ruthless contract. Overall, seems like a pretty solid movie, with some parts exaggerated a bit, but hey, that's any biopic.

text: CLAP!! CLAP!! CLAP!! We open on a pair of black balls smacking another pair of black balls. Sweat flies as the testicular rhythm is heard in the next room by Dr. Dre, drooling and staring at a pair of rickety headphones like a Down Syndrome patient, eventually rocking to the nutsack BEATS cranking louder through the wall. Back in the original room, we see Eazy-E erupt into Ice Cube's asshole balls-deep and bareback, collapsing over Cube in a crack-fueled vomit spasm. With a string of bloody snot danging from his monstrously flaring nostrils and a musical twinkle in his eye, Eazy lovingly grunts into Cube's ear: "AIDS." Meantime -- DJ Yella and MC Ren, the size of ants, masturbate in the corner.  SUPERIMPOSE: "STRAIGHT OUTTA COMPTON" The movie begins!! Credits roll as the five NWA members run through a field of cotton, naked and being chased by five giant sperm cells using their own tails as bullwhips. The sky scrolls images of racial injustice - mostly Vanilla Ice's face - until the five reach the parking lot of a McDonald's, where they are arrested for "invisible exposure." While in prison, the five notice Chuck E Cheese locked up across the corridor. After admitting that he fist-fucked a baby nun, the five refuse to talk to the rat, who proceeds to call them "niggas with attitude." An inspirational score rises as an epiphany rings true on all the five's faces ... except for Ice Cube, who commences to explode Eazy-E's AIDS semen out of his sphincter.

text: I wish I was around during those times to understand what NWA was all about, sure it was violent times, but from what ive heard from my dad, seems like a legendary story that helped me see the truth, my dad made it seem like it was violent for the right reasons, it was people fighting for whats right, not all of it was right, but it was for people to have a voice, im only 15 and i think the world now is a piece of shit, all these motherfuckers cant figure out reality and whats right, all i can really say is thank god my dad had me grow up listening to their music, he wasnt the type to be like "this is a bad influence on my child" it was actually a lesson, and now i fully understand their music, obviously i didnt really turn out fucked up, i dont do drugs, i dont have sex, and i dont fight, actually i turned out to be a pretty scary person because, i know whats right and i will call it out, NWA has basically raised me, and basically i cant thank them enough for that

text: My daughter was sent a audio tape from Compton CA. 25 years ago of N.W.A. when she was 15. Now she is 40 and was the only one that knew all the words to all the songs when we went to see the movie which was absolutely brilliant and eye-opening. I have always believed that people are a product of their environment. When my daughter and I moved into the city I didn't understand why African-Americans hated the police so much... until she and I were regularly harassed,ill-treated,and bullied for passing through "black neighborhoods".  I have even had money stollen by police. They said they saw me coming out of a " dope-hole" even though I never got out of the car,and my money was "drug money" and that is why it was seized. No doubt that it was not logged into evidence. Police in Baltimore City (at least most of them) are rude,corrupt,and regularly abuse their power.

text: It's interesting to see things from my high school years now starting to recycle for a new generation.  At the time when N.W.A. was doing their stuff, I was more into Public Enemy and east coast artists even though I'm from Los Angeles.  When Ice Cube went solo and Tupac released his first album, I started listening more to west coast rap styles.  I've been an active poet for about 4 years now...and much of that has been due to hip hop / rap music from 1988 to 1998.  It will be interesting to see more films with stories about the music of that era.  Check out my poetry here > www.vimeo.com/thebookofsultry

text: *Reasons for why this movie is a good movie, but shitty as a biopic.* (feel free to provide what I left out)  1. They cut out D.O.C when he wrote lyrics for some of the members, had very few scenes with him.   2. The Arabian Prince was an early member of N.W.A, but he was nowhere to be seen i the movie.   3. Vanilla Ice funded Death Row, and the movie didn't have him or said anything about that.   4. 2pac sang "Hail Marry", which is not true to the real shit, cause by the time that song was made Dre already left Death Row.   5. Eazy E didn't have a final conversation with Dre or Yella in reality. Instead Dre whispered something to Eazy while he was comatose, and later Eazy died.  6. Dj Yella didn't drink in real life, yet you see him drinking and getting wasted. He didn't even smoke weed at that time or have a bitch in his lap every 5 minutes.  7.Eazy never went broke IRL, he had Bone Thugs-N-Harmony by his side and had 30 million dollars, before his death.    8.The first N.W.A concert "Fuck the police", didn't go down like that. There were some dudes throwing firecrackers on the stage, and the N.W.A stopped the concert and bounced back to their hotel, then they were told that some sexy girls wanted to see them in the lobby, and instead they got the police, who arrested them without any trouble. NOT that shit in the movie where people throw stuff at cops and arrest the members straight after the concert!   9. Eazy E paid Dre's bail for having unpaid parking tickets for his Mazda RX7, not for disobeying an order from a cop or standing his ground.   10. Cube didn't leave N.W.A by himself, he first consulted publicist Pat Charbonnet about leaving, and then took that decision.  11. Dre was physically abusive with lots of women, and yet we don't see that in the movie. Neither Dee Barnes, MIchele, or Tairrie B was in the movie getting punched or in the movie at all!   12. J.J  Fad are not in this movie, and they were integral to the N.W.A story in reality and their album Supersonic paved the way for their male counterparts by offering a poppy alternative to the gangster rap NWA would become known for, and - by hitting #33 on the Billboard Charts - legitimized Ruthless Records with a commercially successful album, enabling Straight Outta Compton to become the hit we know it as today.   13. Da Lench Mobb was attacked by above the law, but Cube didn't beat any of them, instead he ran away with some help from King Sun. Cube couldn't scrap IRL like he did in the movie.   14.  Yo Yo, a female rapper who worked with Ice Cube after he left N.W.A., was nowhere to be found. Nor are women who worked with Dre later in his career, like Jewell and the Lady of Rage. They both contributed tremendously to the ultimate sound of the classic album The Chronic.   15. MC Ren was a big part of the group, yet he's hardly doing anything in the movie, and looks like an extra.   16. Jerry didn't break up the crew, it was Eazy along with Jerry who broke it up. None of them fools understood a shit about the music industry and contracts, so Jerry was maybe not as bad as everyone seems to think, and Eazy didn't give a shit if he got taken care of the most, while the others didn't.   17.  'The beef with dre and Eazy aint in the movie, "A real Mothafucking G", also ain't in it.   18. Dre got tons of kids, nothing mentioned about that shit in the movie.  19. Ice Cube wasn't the only one writing the songs for N.W.A, The D.O.C did along with Mc Ren. The movie shows Cube doing that and it ain't right!  20. Cube's family life, with middle class income wasn't portrayed in the movie. Cube wasn't poor, he had two parents, and he went to phoenix institute of technology, earning a 2 year degree in architectural drafting. Far from gangsta. Not in the movie also!  21. Also Dre, Cube, and MC Ren didn't show up for his funeral, like the movie lies about. Only Dj Yella attended Eazy's funeral, none of the others, something the movie ignores.   22. Eazy had seven children with six different women, nothing mentioned about that in the movie.  23. D.O.C came up with the name Def Row, but Dre changed it to Death Row and used that name.   24. The group had no agreed to not perform Fuck The police at first, but they got mad at the promoter because of some arguments about the money they'd get and performed it anyway. This ain't in the movie.   25. We didn't see how every N.W.A member helped Eazy with his album 'Eazy-Duz-It' and how Eazy didn't want to pay them for their help for  his album, but only for N.W.A album. Basically Eazy was selfish, along with Cube and Dre. Dre didn't pay D.O.C for his work on The Chronic. Cube felt like he was better, because e wrote half a N.W.A album, forgetting Mc Ren's part about writing.   26. Eazy owned the company, he got 25%, Heller got 20% as a manager, and that leaves  80% split five ways, Jerry didn't do nothing wrong, and if he did, you better tell me how, or the movie fails to depict him right. Jerry was portrayed wrong.   27. Eazy E came up to Jerry Heller first, the scene where Heller walks up to Eazy is not true at all.   28. Their album 'Efil4Zaggin was not mentioned or showcased in the  movie, and it was the album with more variety, controversy and misogyny than any other N.W.A album. It should have been in the movie!
